<paragraph blockId="31.[132,776,280,464]" box="[132,222,280,306]" pageId="31" pageNumber="288">REMARK</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[132,776,280,464]" pageId="31" pageNumber="288">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[132,239,311,337]" class="Asteroidea" family="Echinasteridae" genus="Echinaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spinulosida" pageId="31" pageNumber="288" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[132,239,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="288">E. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits Indian Seas according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Dujardin &amp; Hupe" firstAuthor="Dujardin" pageId="31" pageNumber="288" refId="ref43636" refString="DUJARDIN F. &amp; HUPE H. 1862. - Histoire naturelle des zoophytes echinodermes. Librairie encyclopedique De Roret, Paris, 625 p. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10122" type="book" year="1862">Dujardin &amp; Hupé (1862)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[132,776,280,464]" pageId="31" pageNumber="288">
The species shares all the characteristics of the common Indian Ocean species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perrier" authorityYear="1869" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[339,554,406,432]" class="Asteroidea" family="Echinasteridae" genus="Echinaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spinulosida" pageId="31" pageNumber="288" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis box="[339,554,406,432]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="288">Echinaster purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, having a reticulated skeleton and abactinal plates arranged in longitudinal series.
</paragraph>
